<i>it's the first week,
nothing much really happens.</i>

04:20.595 --> 04:23.264
- Make any new friends?
<i>- It's funny, actually.</i>

04:23.473 --> 04:25.391
All those kids
that I've gone to school with

04:25.600 --> 04:27.310
since kindergarten...

04:27.518 --> 04:31.022
<i>...they all left,
so...they're all new kids</i>

04:31.231 --> 04:32.857
and they all wanted
to be friends with me.

04:35.652 --> 04:37.946
And it was pretty sweet.

05:25.576 --> 05:26.995
Who are you?

05:29.622 --> 05:30.790
My name is John.

05:37.755 --> 05:39.882
<i>And welcome back
to Clayton's WXPC</i>

05:40.091 --> 05:41.759
<i>it's just about
the top of the hour.</i>

05:41.968 --> 05:43.386
<i>Some startling new
developments on a story</i>

05:43.594 --> 05:46.139
<i>we've been following
for the last 48 hours.</i>

05:46.347 --> 05:48.891
<i>The death of a Clayton man,
Jeb Jolly, aged 53</i>

05:49.100 --> 05:51.394
<i>is now under
police investigation.</i>

05:51.602 --> 05:53.396
<i>The local mechanic's body
was found yesterday</i>

05:53.604 --> 05:55.148
<i>by one woman who likened
the violent scene</i>

05:55.356 --> 05:58.234
<i>to, quote,
"A bizarre animal attack."</i>

05:58.443 --> 05:59.569
<i>Clayton County
Police Department</i>

05:59.777 --> 06:01.195
<i>have declined to comment,
citing the need</i>

06:01.404 --> 06:03.239
<i>for an official
coroner's report.</i>

06:03.448 --> 06:05.742
<i>Jolly's family
asking only for our prayers.</i>

06:27.930 --> 06:30.475
Hey, Principal Layton
wants to see you.

06:43.738 --> 06:45.365
<i>Mrs. Cleaver,
take a seat please.</i>

06:53.456 --> 06:56.167
<i>John, adolescence
can be a difficult time.</i>

06:57.293 --> 06:59.504
It's normal to be
interested in the world

06:59.712 --> 07:01.381
and all of its problems.

07:01.589 --> 07:04.967
<i>Normal to be drawn
to death and murder.</i>

07:05.176 --> 07:08.679
<i>But, unfortunately, you can go
too far down that road.</i>

07:08.888 --> 07:11.140
Too far away from...

07:11.349 --> 07:13.935
Well, normal thoughts.

07:17.230 --> 07:19.065
What do you say, John?

07:24.112 --> 07:25.988
I'm interested in
how many times you felt

07:26.197 --> 07:28.157
it was necessary
to say the word "normal."

07:31.160 --> 07:32.703
<i>It's not like there's a whole
lot to say about Einstein.</i>

07:32.912 --> 07:34.956
I mean, he discovered
E equals MC square

07:35.164 --> 07:37.041
and nuclear bombs but that's it.

07:37.291 --> 07:39.377
I'm lucky I got
half a page at all.

07:39.585 --> 07:40.920
And you missed
two points for length

07:41.129 --> 07:43.297
you missed another two
for spelling.

07:43.506 --> 07:44.382
I mean, you managed
to spell Einstein

07:44.590 --> 07:45.466
a different way every time.

07:45.675 --> 07:46.968
That's creativity.

07:47.176 --> 07:49.387
No, that's remarkable.
That's amazing.

07:52.598 --> 07:54.058
Hoo! Say, you guys, uh

07:54.267 --> 07:56.227
<i>you guys catch that smell?</i>

07:56.436 --> 07:58.187
Smells of something dead.

07:58.396 --> 08:00.064
Something rotting.

08:11.909 --> 08:13.161
Freak.

08:19.834 --> 08:22.170
So, what psycho
did you write about?

08:22.378 --> 08:25.047
Dennis Rader, uh, the,
uh, the BTK Killer.

08:27.175 --> 08:28.468
That's how he signed all of his
letters to the media

08:28.676 --> 08:30.970
as "Bind, torture, kill."

08:31.179 --> 08:32.889
How many people did he kill?

08:33.097 --> 08:36.058
Maybe 10, they're not, they're
not sure but could be more.

08:36.267 --> 08:37.184
<i>Only 10?</i>

08:37.393 --> 08:38.727
<i>The guy you wrote
about last year</i>

08:38.936 --> 08:40.313
was way better at it.

08:40.520 --> 08:41.563
<i>Jeffrey Dahmer.</i>

08:41.772 --> 08:42.648
He was a cannibal and he kept

08:42.857 --> 08:44.901
severed heads in his freezer.

08:45.109 --> 08:46.319
<i>I remember your pictures now.</i>

08:46.527 --> 08:48.154
They gave me nightmares.

08:48.362 --> 08:49.280
Nightmares are nothin' man.

08:49.489 --> 08:51.157
Those pictures gave me
a therapist.

09:16.557 --> 09:17.934
Oh, what up?

09:18.142 --> 09:19.560
<i>That black cloud
above ya's growing.</i>

09:20.853 --> 09:23.606
I broke one of my rules.

09:23.814 --> 09:25.733
- Stalking anybody?
- No.

09:25.942 --> 09:28.027
What else?

09:28.236 --> 09:30.947
Have you heard about
the Macdonald triad?

09:31.155 --> 09:34.200
Three traits shared by 95
percent of all serial killers

09:34.408 --> 09:36.953
bedwetting, pyromania,
animal cruelty.

09:37.161 --> 09:39.330
<i>You do, I admit,
have all three.</i>

09:40.998 --> 09:43.834
What really gets me is...

09:44.001 --> 09:46.170
...you know, a -- animal cruelty
predicts violent behavior...

09:47.880 --> 09:49.298
...but until I read that
I -- I didn't think

09:49.507 --> 09:51.884
it was wrong...you know.

09:52.093 --> 09:53.678
What else?

09:56.222 --> 09:57.390
Well, if I -- I -- I...

09:57.598 --> 10:00.434
If I'm thinking about
hurting a person, then...

10:00.643 --> 10:03.312
...you know, I'll just
give them a compliment.

10:03.521 --> 10:06.607
If somebody's really bugging me
to the point where...

10:06.816 --> 10:08.985
...when I think about
killing them, then...

10:09.193 --> 10:10.111
...I'll just, I'll just smile

10:10.319 --> 10:12.196
and I'll say
something nice...you know?

10:16.409 --> 10:18.119
- Is that hot chocolate?
- Uh-huh.

10:18.327 --> 10:20.329
I'm good.

10:20.538 --> 10:23.708
John, you have
a -- a lot of predictors

10:23.916 --> 10:26.502
for serial killer behavior,
but

10:26.711 --> 10:28.379
<i>predictors are just that,
they predict</i>

10:28.588 --> 10:30.798
<i>what might happen,
not what will happen.</i>

10:31.007 --> 10:33.426
<i>You're in control
of your own destiny.</i>

10:33.634 --> 10:35.928
<i>You're a good person, John.
That's important.</i>

10:46.439 --> 10:47.398
Hey, John?

10:47.607 --> 10:49.233
- Yeah, Mr. Crowley?
- Come here.

10:51.777 --> 10:53.362
What do you know
about smartphones?

10:53.571 --> 10:54.989
Uh, I don't know.

10:55.197 --> 10:57.199
What do you, what do you need?

10:57.408 --> 10:59.577
I want to send
my wife a kiss.

10:59.785 --> 11:01.078
You want to send her a kiss?

11:01.287 --> 11:02.705
<i>You're supposed to be able
to take photos</i>

11:02.913 --> 11:04.290
<i>and send them to each other.</i>

11:04.498 --> 11:06.459
- Alright, um...
<i>- Show me how it's done.</i>

11:06.667 --> 11:09.170
- Well, so, it's that button.
- Uh-huh.

11:09.378 --> 11:10.963
And then...

11:11.172 --> 11:12.298
...you can use this one
to take the picture, so...

11:12.506 --> 11:14.175
- Oh, oh...
- Here you go.

11:18.846 --> 11:20.806
Okay.

11:21.015 --> 11:21.891
And there you go.

11:23.517 --> 11:25.353
Good Lord,
she's gonna be in shock

11:25.561 --> 11:26.479
that's for sure.

11:58.260 --> 12:00.971
Brooke?
Come on down, dinner's ready.

12:44.932 --> 12:47.810
Relax, he's dead.
He's going nowhere fast.

12:50.187 --> 12:51.063
Is that Jeb Jolly?

12:51.272 --> 12:53.315
Oh-ho, yes.

12:55.192 --> 12:56.986
<i>Hey...</i>

12:57.194 --> 12:59.613
<i>...you surviving?</i>

12:59.822 --> 13:01.157
Uh...

13:01.365 --> 13:02.825
Are you?

13:03.033 --> 13:05.161
<i>I'm not the one
who has to live with mom.</i>

13:05.369 --> 13:07.329
<i>You hear from dad?</i>

13:07.538 --> 13:08.497
No.

13:08.706 --> 13:09.832
You?

13:10.040 --> 13:11.333
Rarely.

13:11.542 --> 13:13.252
I ask him for money sometimes.

13:14.170 --> 13:16.338
- John?
- Yeah?

13:16.547 --> 13:18.674
- Dr. Neblin told me.
- What?

13:18.883 --> 13:21.302
That you think you're going
to kill somebody.

13:23.345 --> 13:25.514
That's funny,
'cause that's not what I said.

13:25.723 --> 13:28.434
What I said was that,
I follow very strict rules

13:28.642 --> 13:30.770
to keep me from doing
anything wrong.

13:30.978 --> 13:32.938
Seems like
you'd be happy about that.

13:33.147 --> 13:34.398
Happy...

13:34.607 --> 13:36.442
...is not a son
who has to follow rules

13:36.650 --> 13:38.194
to keep himself from
killing people

13:38.402 --> 13:40.446
happy is not a psychologist

13:40.654 --> 13:43.240
telling me my son
is a sociopath.

13:43.449 --> 13:46.243
He actually said that?
That's kinda cool.

13:46.952 --> 13:48.037
Antisocial--

13:48.245 --> 13:49.038
Hate to dump this on you

13:49.246 --> 13:50.664
this time of night, April.

13:50.873 --> 13:51.874
It's a hell of a thing.

13:53.417 --> 13:55.127
I think the damage
is done, mom.

13:55.336 --> 13:57.505
What dive
are you heading to tonight?

13:57.713 --> 13:59.298
Somewhere with more
living people then here

13:59.507 --> 14:01.467
that's for sure. Have fun.

14:26.700 --> 14:29.203
<i>Oh, for the love of Mike.</i>

14:29.411 --> 14:31.413
<i>- I call organs.
- Fine.</i>

14:45.010 --> 14:46.679
<i>- Dang it, Ron.
- What?</i>

14:46.887 --> 14:49.306
Well, we're missing a kidney.

14:49.515 --> 14:50.724
<i>I've gone through
the bag twice.</i>

14:50.933 --> 14:52.601
You think Ron would manage
to send us all the organs

14:52.810 --> 14:54.144
for crying out loud.

14:55.938 --> 14:57.606
Well...

14:57.815 --> 14:59.483
What if the person
who killed him took it?

14:59.692 --> 15:01.026
- That's...
<i>- It's totally possible.</i>

15:01.235 --> 15:02.111
<i>Look at that.</i>

15:02.778 --> 15:03.904
<i>It'll be on the forms.</i>

15:04.113 --> 15:06.031
<i>I don't think so.
Oh, wait, here.</i>

15:06.240 --> 15:08.576
"Left kidney removed
via incisions to

15:08.784 --> 15:11.161
renal artery, veins and ureter."

15:11.370 --> 15:12.913
So he had it removed?

15:13.122 --> 15:16.625
No, there's no record
of that, it's just not there.

15:24.925 --> 15:26.635
<i>This is Ted Rath,
live at the scene</i>

15:26.844 --> 15:28.721
<i>where the ambulance has
just left and as you can see</i>

15:28.929 --> 15:31.432
<i>the police and a crowd
are gathering here in Clayton</i>

15:31.640 --> 15:33.350
<i>a normally peaceful town,
where a killer has struck</i>

15:33.559 --> 15:35.561
<i>possibly for the second time</i>

15:35.769 --> 15:38.606
<i>leaving a dead body and
a terrified town in his wake.</i>

15:38.814 --> 15:41.358
Stupid, stupid,
the last thing this town needs

15:41.567 --> 15:44.403
is panic about a mass murderer.

15:44.612 --> 15:46.780
I think the last thing
we need are the killings.

15:46.989 --> 15:48.532
<i>Now details are sketchy
at this time</i>

15:48.741 --> 15:50.993
<i>but what I have been able to
ascertain is there was a small</i>

15:51.201 --> 15:53.454
<i>pool of oil
or some black sludge found</i>

15:53.662 --> 15:55.623
<i>near the body of local farmer,
Dave Byrd.</i>

15:55.831 --> 15:56.916
<i>We will, of course,
be giving you details</i>

15:57.124 --> 15:58.083
<i>as they become available.</i>

15:58.292 --> 16:00.336
<i>This is a 5 Live
news exclusive.</i>

16:00.544 --> 16:02.922
<i>Death stalks
America's heartland.</i>

16:04.965 --> 16:07.676
Okay, so the first question
of psychological profiling is

16:07.885 --> 16:09.511
what's the killer doing
he doesn't absolutely

16:09.720 --> 16:11.221
have to be doing?

16:11.430 --> 16:13.390
Dude, I think
it's a werewolf.

16:13.599 --> 16:15.601
It's not a werewolf.

16:15.809 --> 16:17.478
Dude, did you see the news?

16:17.686 --> 16:20.439
It has the intelligence of man
with the furiocity of a beast.

16:20.648 --> 16:21.857
- What is that supposed to be?
- It's not a werewolf.

16:22.066 --> 16:23.484
Werewolves aren't real.

16:23.692 --> 16:25.319
The stories of them
probably started

16:25.527 --> 16:27.029
from serial killers, you know.

16:27.237 --> 16:30.240
Vampires too. It's just men
who hunt and kill other men.

16:30.449 --> 16:33.869
So assuming a basic goal
of trying to kill somebody.

16:34.078 --> 16:35.621
All you really need to do
is shoot them, right?

16:35.829 --> 16:36.789
Yeah.

16:36.997 --> 16:38.832
So what's he doing
that he doesn't have to do?

16:39.041 --> 16:41.669
Well, he's s -- stabbing him,
rippin' into him.

16:41.877 --> 16:42.628
Exactly, yeah, that's the,

16:42.836 --> 16:43.754
that's the first thing,
you know.

16:43.963 --> 16:45.756
He approaches 'em in person.

16:45.965 --> 16:47.800
Probably means he wants to be
close to the victims. What else?

16:48.008 --> 16:50.886
He attacked during the night,
in the dark.

16:51.095 --> 16:53.681
I think that's probably
just something he had to do.

16:53.889 --> 16:56.600
Doesn't that count
for your list?

16:56.809 --> 16:59.061
I mean, it's,
it's not a unique trait.

16:59.269 --> 17:01.689
Nobody who kills somebody else
wants to be seen.

17:01.897 --> 17:04.148
Just put it on your list,
I mean...

17:04.358 --> 17:06.234
...not everything in this
has to be your idea.

17:18.038 --> 17:19.498
Ted Bundy...

17:19.707 --> 17:20.874
...the one that they, uh...

17:21.125 --> 17:23.002
...they coined
the term serial killer for.

17:25.045 --> 17:28.716
He said that
after you killed somebody...

17:28.924 --> 17:31.176
You know, if you had
enough time with them,

17:31.385 --> 17:33.387
they could be whoever
you wanted them to be.

17:34.722 --> 17:37.891
<i>You're weird man.</i>

17:48.694 --> 17:50.904
I hate Halloween.
It's absurd, you know.

17:51.113 --> 17:52.948
This is the,
this is the night when

17:53.157 --> 17:55.492
evil spirits are supposed
to walk the Earth.

17:55.701 --> 17:59.163
You know, druids burning kids
in wicker baskets, you know.

17:59.371 --> 18:01.040
My position is vulnerable
out here, boys

18:01.248 --> 18:03.250
<i>let's stay alert
and keep moving.</i>

18:03.459 --> 18:04.835
Can't you just tell him
to go away?

18:05.044 --> 18:06.628
Nah, leave him alone.

18:06.837 --> 18:09.465
He's convinced the killer
is gonna come out and get us.

18:09.673 --> 18:11.717
Plus, it makes him happy.
Right, dad?

18:11.925 --> 18:13.969
<i>Let's just hurry up
and get the hell outta here.</i>

18:14.178 --> 18:16.847
<i>Dad, you said we could
stay out till 9:30.</i>

18:35.908 --> 18:38.786
<i>Trick or treat?</i>

18:38.994 --> 18:41.914
You boy's shouldn't be
out this late.

18:42.122 --> 18:44.875
Yeah. It's not safe
with a killer out there.

18:45.084 --> 18:46.585
That's what I'm saying.

18:46.794 --> 18:48.378
You boys be careful.

19:28.168 --> 19:29.711
Are you It?

19:29.920 --> 19:31.922
Am I what?

19:32.131 --> 19:35.008
The clown from "It,"
that Stephen King book.

19:35.217 --> 19:38.345
No.

19:38.554 --> 19:40.139
I was thinking about
dressing up as my mother

19:40.347 --> 19:43.392
but I was worried
what my therapist would say.

19:43.600 --> 19:45.018
You gonna juggle
for us, freak?

19:50.899 --> 19:52.401
That's a really
clever costume.

19:52.609 --> 19:53.861
<i>You know, it looks great.</i>

19:54.069 --> 19:55.529
It's really inventive and the

19:55.737 --> 19:57.698
the bullet hole looks...
really authentic.

20:00.200 --> 20:02.369
You know this is a party
for normal people? Right?

20:02.578 --> 20:03.912
So why don't you go home

20:04.121 --> 20:06.290
to your undertaking
slut of a mother.

20:06.498 --> 20:07.916
Alright?

20:09.793 --> 20:11.962
What are you smiling about?

20:12.171 --> 20:15.465
I've been clinically
diagnosed with sociopathy, Rob.

20:15.674 --> 20:16.842
To me, you're an object.

20:17.050 --> 20:18.927
You know, you're a,
you're a thing.

20:19.136 --> 20:21.597
You're about as important to me
as a cardboard box.

20:21.805 --> 20:24.808
And the -- the thing about
cardboard boxes...

20:25.017 --> 20:26.268
..is that...

20:26.476 --> 20:28.604
You know they're totally boring
on the outside, right?

20:28.812 --> 20:31.982
But...sometimes,
if you cut 'em open

20:32.191 --> 20:35.027
there'll be something
interesting inside.

20:35.235 --> 20:36.528
You know, and so,
while you're saying

20:36.737 --> 20:38.697
all these boring things to me

20:38.906 --> 20:40.449
I'm thinking about
what it'd be like

20:40.657 --> 20:42.159
to cut you open.

20:44.369 --> 20:47.873
But I -- I don't wanna,
I don't wanna be that person.

20:48.081 --> 20:49.833
And so, I have a rule

20:50.042 --> 20:52.628
that anytime somebody
says something to me

20:52.836 --> 20:55.464
where I -- I think about,
you know, cuttin' 'em.

20:57.216 --> 21:00.093
I -- I -- I just smile
and I say something nice.

21:00.302 --> 21:02.054
So that's why
I say to you,

21:02.262 --> 21:05.515
Rob Anders of 232
Carnation Street.

21:06.642 --> 21:08.936
You are a
really great guy.

21:13.649 --> 21:14.816
You're a freak.

21:26.495 --> 21:27.412
You're not a freak.

22:21.800 --> 22:22.968
<i>John.</i>

22:27.639 --> 22:29.308
What is this?

22:32.436 --> 22:33.729
It's...

22:35.314 --> 22:36.773
John...

22:36.982 --> 22:39.026
...wash up and get out.

22:39.234 --> 22:39.818
Mom, it's -- it's not...

22:40.027 --> 22:41.820
I should be stronger
with you. This is my fault.

22:42.029 --> 22:42.988
Mom, there -- there should be
something missing.

22:43.739 --> 22:45.574
There should be an organ
missing to fit the profile.

22:57.419 --> 22:58.754
Go!

23:04.760 --> 23:06.928
This door will be locked
in future!

23:11.767 --> 23:12.768
<i>Who told you?</i>

23:13.560 --> 23:16.021
He told a school counselor,
who told me.

23:16.229 --> 23:19.024
Lucky for you, she didn't tell
Principal Layton.

23:20.609 --> 23:22.527
<i>Apparently you gave him
nightmares, John.</i>

23:24.029 --> 23:25.364
Rob Anders is a bully.

23:25.572 --> 23:27.199
<i>Doesn't mean you can threaten
to kill him.</i>

23:27.407 --> 23:28.575
I, I didn't.

23:28.784 --> 23:31.495
And then there's
what happened in the mortuary.

23:31.703 --> 23:32.829
What is it?

23:33.038 --> 23:34.748
<i>What set you off?</i>

23:37.000 --> 23:38.585
It all just feels so close.

23:39.836 --> 23:41.963
<i>This is, this is nowhere.</i>

23:42.672 --> 23:44.091
It isn't supposed
to happen here,

23:44.299 --> 23:46.093
it's supposed to be
somewhere else, you know?

23:48.887 --> 23:51.390
Okay. Let me ask you this.

23:51.598 --> 23:53.767
<i>Who were you talking to just
before Rob Anders upset you?</i>

23:53.975 --> 23:56.770
Oh, it was just some girl.

23:56.978 --> 23:58.897
<i>She have a name?</i>

23:59.398 --> 24:01.191
<i>Her, her name is Brooke.</i>

24:01.400 --> 24:02.442
Cute?

24:03.902 --> 24:05.987
Little young for you, doctor.

24:08.281 --> 24:11.701
Yes. Barrow's goldeneye.
Come here.

24:11.910 --> 24:13.036
Have a look at this.

24:15.997 --> 24:17.249
Here.

24:18.250 --> 24:20.043
Straight over there.
Have a look.

24:22.754 --> 24:23.547
<i>Do you see it?</i>

24:23.755 --> 24:24.798
Oh...

24:26.550 --> 24:28.718
Yeah. A duck.

24:28.927 --> 24:30.887
That's a very rare duck.

24:31.096 --> 24:32.305
<i>So don't go killin' it.</i>

24:33.890 --> 24:36.268
<i>I haven't seen one of them
in over 5 years.</i>

24:37.310 --> 24:39.354
<i>Actually you can see the eyes,
that they're beautiful,</i>

24:39.563 --> 24:40.188
<i>they're beautiful.</i>

24:40.397 --> 24:42.399
<i>more amber, really, than gold.</i>

24:42.607 --> 24:45.610
<i>It catches the light, no matter
where they are. Exceptional.</i>

25:53.637 --> 25:55.096
<i>- Hey, you fishing?</i>
- Huh?

25:55.305 --> 25:57.557
<i>Are you goin' fishing?</i>

25:57.766 --> 25:58.975
Ice fishing.

25:59.184 --> 26:01.269
<i>Do you need a hand
with that stuff here?</i>

26:01.478 --> 26:04.856
<i>Let me just... take that
off your hands.</i>

26:05.065 --> 26:07.275
<i>Yeah, I used to go fishing
all the time up north.</i>

26:07.484 --> 26:08.109
<i>Oh, is that right?</i>

26:08.318 --> 26:09.444
<i>Yeah, my uncle has a cabin...</i>

26:09.653 --> 26:11.071
- Oh, good.
- Oh, yeah.

26:11.279 --> 26:13.698
Yeah, you mind if I come along?

26:13.907 --> 26:15.242
Uh, well...

26:18.703 --> 26:21.331
How far off you going?

26:21.540 --> 26:24.543
Well, far enough.

26:24.751 --> 26:26.294
<i>You're gonna need a -- a hat
out there alright?</i>

27:10.547 --> 27:11.715
Uh...

28:10.398 --> 28:12.651
...I bought you a hat.

29:19.926 --> 29:21.302
Here.

29:29.644 --> 29:31.688
<i>We're not gonna tell your mom
about this, okay?</i>

29:31.896 --> 29:34.357
Right now she is simultaneously
trying to stuff a turkey

29:34.566 --> 29:36.109
and wipe away tears.

29:36.317 --> 29:37.610
She's crying?

29:37.819 --> 29:39.529
Uh-huh.

29:39.738 --> 29:41.489
Mother of all blow ups
yesterday with Lauren

29:41.698 --> 29:45.201
who's now not coming
to Thanksgiving dinner tonight.

29:45.410 --> 29:47.412
That leaves you and me, sport.

29:47.620 --> 29:48.997
<i>Go and wash.</i>

29:49.205 --> 29:52.292
I need you to come out of your
head for a couple hours, okay?

29:52.500 --> 29:53.877
Give her a hand...

29:54.085 --> 29:56.337
...make her realize she still
has one loving child left.

29:57.172 --> 29:58.381
Or at least pretend.

30:09.517 --> 30:11.311
Urgh!

30:16.191 --> 30:19.569
Oh, I had to stop by Ron's
for that file he forgot

30:19.778 --> 30:21.905
and he, uh, he told me a joke.

30:22.113 --> 30:23.948
- You wanna hear it?
- Sure.

30:24.157 --> 30:26.618
<i>What's small and grey
and screws in the walls?</i>

30:26.785 --> 30:28.787
I don't know...

30:39.964 --> 30:42.050
<i>John, can you...</i>

30:42.258 --> 30:44.260
<i>scoot across
to the Watsons and...</i>

30:44.469 --> 30:45.845
<i>ask Bev for some vanilla?</i>

30:47.138 --> 30:48.431
Uh...

30:48.640 --> 30:50.517
Yeah, sure.

31:02.403 --> 31:03.905
<i>Keep it up you loser.</i>

31:04.113 --> 31:05.448
<i>Hi, John.</i>

31:06.991 --> 31:09.160
- Uh, vanilla.
- Vanilla?

31:09.369 --> 31:10.995
Uh, yeah, vanilla.

31:11.204 --> 31:12.747
Vanilla, like, ice cream?

31:12.956 --> 31:15.542
Um, you know,
I'm not, I'm not really sure.

31:15.750 --> 31:17.585
Mom just said we needed some.

31:17.794 --> 31:19.128
Here you go, John.

31:20.296 --> 31:22.257
It's for cooking.

31:28.680 --> 31:29.556
<i>This is Ted Rath
with an update</i>

31:29.764 --> 31:31.391
<i>on the Clayton
killer situation.</i>

31:31.599 --> 31:32.892
<i>Now this reporter
has discovered there is</i>

31:33.101 --> 31:34.602
<i>an Emmet T. Openshaw</i>

31:34.811 --> 31:36.855
<i>an Arizona man who disappeared
from his home</i>

31:37.063 --> 31:38.940
<i>42 years ago.</i>

31:39.148 --> 31:40.066
<i>He was 30 at the time.</i>

31:40.275 --> 31:41.526
<i>Police found signs
of struggle</i>

31:41.734 --> 31:44.028
<i>but there was no body
found at the scene.</i>

31:44.237 --> 31:45.363
<i>Now the reason
this crime connects</i>

31:45.572 --> 31:46.656
<i>to what's happening here
in Clayton county</i>

31:46.865 --> 31:48.700
<i>is they found a similar pile</i>

31:48.908 --> 31:51.035
<i>of black oil
at the crime scene.</i>

32:17.937 --> 32:19.480
<i>Good morning, Mrs. Crowley,
um, I thought</i>

32:19.689 --> 32:21.441
I could shovel
your steps for you.

32:24.235 --> 32:25.904
Good morning, Kay.

32:26.112 --> 32:28.323
It snowed, so...

32:28.531 --> 32:30.366
I could shovel your drive
if you like, uh...

32:34.162 --> 32:36.372
Good morning, Mrs. Crowley.

32:36.581 --> 32:37.957
Good morning, Mrs. Crowley.

32:57.602 --> 32:58.937
John?

33:01.189 --> 33:03.191
Um...

33:03.399 --> 33:05.109
Hi, uh, the snow.

33:05.276 --> 33:07.236
I thought I'd...

33:07.445 --> 33:09.739
Well, that would be
very nice. Thank you.

33:09.948 --> 33:11.824
Sure thing.

33:40.561 --> 33:42.480
<i>Ah, it's a beautiful
day, John.</i>

33:44.649 --> 33:46.109
Makes you glad to be alive.

33:54.826 --> 33:57.120
Here you go, John.
Hot chocolate, your favorite.

33:58.454 --> 33:59.872
Thank you.

34:01.165 --> 34:02.959
<i>Every single time.</i>

34:07.463 --> 34:09.257
<i>Where are they?</i>

34:09.465 --> 34:11.342
Your forehead, dear.

34:45.376 --> 34:46.918
Takes the lungs...

34:49.797 --> 34:51.466
...takes the kidney...

34:54.469 --> 34:56.054
...took an arm.

35:03.478 --> 35:04.771
What next?

35:54.403 --> 35:57.115
- Uh...
- Okay.

35:57.323 --> 35:58.407
Yeah.

36:21.180 --> 36:22.932
<i>Repeating
tonight's top story</i>

36:23.141 --> 36:26.102
<i>the FBI has confirmed
a positive DNA match</i>

36:26.310 --> 36:27.895
<i>between that of
the Clayton county murders</i>

36:28.104 --> 36:29.230
<i>and Emmet T. Openshaw</i>

36:29.438 --> 36:32.441
<i>the Arizona man
who disappeared in 1971.</i>

36:32.650 --> 36:34.944
<i>Details are coming in, and
the investigation is ongoing.</i>

36:40.366 --> 36:42.410
That is some little woman
you got there, Bill.

36:42.618 --> 36:44.203
Oh, yeah.

36:44.412 --> 36:46.747
<i>Oh, by the way she had
to go powder her nose.</i>

36:46.956 --> 36:48.749
Oh, hey, I hope you don't mind
if I, uh

36:48.958 --> 36:49.750
take her for another spin.

36:49.959 --> 36:51.252
Oh, no, no, no.

36:51.460 --> 36:53.629
- I got some energy left.
- Good.

36:55.006 --> 36:56.757
Well, here's to ya.

36:59.051 --> 37:00.845
Oop, there's Kay.

37:01.053 --> 37:02.805
You don't mind, huh?
Take care now.

37:11.522 --> 37:13.441
Uh...

37:14.192 --> 37:15.526
Ah!

37:58.444 --> 37:59.695
Thank you.

38:07.328 --> 38:08.871
Hey...

38:10.081 --> 38:11.874
Eat you own plate.

38:12.124 --> 38:12.917
<i>John?</i>

38:23.552 --> 38:25.429
I can't believe
you followed me.

38:25.638 --> 38:27.014
I can't believe you were
having dinner with my therapist.

38:27.223 --> 38:28.933
Don't be silly, John.

38:29.141 --> 38:32.061
Grant and I meet sometimes
to discuss your progress,

38:32.270 --> 38:34.522
a progress I am failing
to appreciate right now.

38:34.730 --> 38:36.524
Did I interrupt a date?

38:36.732 --> 38:38.234
Is that even ethical?

38:38.442 --> 38:40.194
It's, it's just
the first right up ahead.

38:40.403 --> 38:41.779
Thanks, April.

38:41.988 --> 38:43.030
Actually John's doing okay.

38:43.239 --> 38:44.782
- He is?
- I am?

38:44.991 --> 38:47.034
Sure, tonight, for example, you
were concerned for your mother

38:47.243 --> 38:49.245
with a killer in town.

38:49.453 --> 38:50.830
<i>You really believe
that I followed mom</i>

38:51.038 --> 38:52.540
because I was worried for her?

38:52.748 --> 38:54.292
You may be lacking
in empathy, John,

38:54.500 --> 38:56.752
but you should recognize a life
line when it's thrown at you.

39:14.854 --> 39:16.397
Hi, John.

39:18.983 --> 39:20.484
Hi, John!

39:23.946 --> 39:25.448
Hey.

39:26.324 --> 39:27.283
Extra work?

39:27.491 --> 39:29.410
Oh, it's,
just a project.

39:32.121 --> 39:34.790
Serial killers...fairies...

39:36.083 --> 39:39.628
...witchcraft...folktales.

39:40.796 --> 39:42.131
That's an
interesting combination.

39:44.800 --> 39:46.427
Need any help?

39:46.635 --> 39:48.888
No, I'm, I'm fine.

39:50.681 --> 39:52.308
Okay.

40:12.328 --> 40:14.789
<i>Pretty good job,
if I do say so myself.</i>

40:16.540 --> 40:18.751
<i>Hey, Tommy, you look
downright dangerous.</i>

40:18.959 --> 40:21.003
- Thanks. Good night, Greg.
<i>- Alright.</i>

40:23.130 --> 40:24.882
<i>Okay, Bill.
You're up next.</i>

40:25.091 --> 40:26.550
<i>Let's go.</i>

40:29.470 --> 40:31.472
Oh, boy.

40:31.680 --> 40:33.599
Too much dancing
the other night, huh?

40:36.060 --> 40:38.979
Yeah, well,
we'll...get you looking

40:39.188 --> 40:40.940
real good for the next time
out, okay?

40:43.275 --> 40:44.360
You need a crane there?

40:48.155 --> 40:49.824
So... Boy, it's been
a while, hasn't it?

40:50.032 --> 40:51.700
You -- you -- you want
something fancy today?

40:51.909 --> 40:53.452
Let's do the...
usual.

40:53.661 --> 40:55.704
The usual?
Alright. Hang tight.

40:55.871 --> 40:57.873
These things have to be
done delicately.

40:58.624 --> 41:00.167
Oh, Jesus.

41:01.377 --> 41:03.087
Uh, hang on a second,
I'll -- I'll get a...

41:03.295 --> 41:04.338
I gotta get another
scissors here.

41:04.547 --> 41:06.132
I'll be right back, alright?

41:06.340 --> 41:07.716
Won't be a moment.

41:53.220 --> 41:54.221
Fuck.

42:19.747 --> 42:21.749
<i>Police department.</i>

42:33.928 --> 42:35.387
Well, I guess we better
take a look around.

42:35.596 --> 42:37.765
Oh, no, uh...

42:37.973 --> 42:39.683
They didn't come through here.

42:39.892 --> 42:41.352
<i>Tom, check this out.</i>

42:41.560 --> 42:43.103
<i>There's something in here.</i>

43:43.998 --> 43:44.832
Uh...

43:47.084 --> 43:48.502
<i>Yes, my dear.</i>

43:49.878 --> 43:51.130
<i>Flour?</i>

43:52.798 --> 43:55.634
Uh, whole...
Whole grain?

43:55.843 --> 43:56.885
Oh, good.

43:58.679 --> 44:00.931
Yes, I'll, uh...

44:01.140 --> 44:02.725
I love you too.

44:52.024 --> 44:54.109
<i>This is Ted Rath coming to
you live from Clayton county</i>

44:54.318 --> 44:56.695
<i>where as you can see
tempers are flaring dangerously.</i>

44:56.904 --> 44:58.989
<i>We are at the home
of local barber Greg Olson.</i>

44:59.198 --> 45:00.783
<i>Olson is the owner
of the premises</i>

45:00.991 --> 45:02.910
<i>where the two policemen were
found dead earlier this week</i>

45:03.118 --> 45:04.453
<i>sparking this outrage.</i>

45:04.662 --> 45:05.496
<i>Let's see if we can get a word
from one of these</i>

45:05.704 --> 45:08.248
<i>concerned citizens.
Excuse me, sir, sir, sir!</i>

45:08.457 --> 45:09.583
<i>What to do you hope
to accomplish with this?</i>

45:09.792 --> 45:12.586
<i>Uh, well, as you can see,
people are angry</i>

45:12.795 --> 45:14.922
<i>and -- and -- and things
are getting out of hand.</i>

45:15.130 --> 45:16.173
<i>What is your name, sir?</i>

45:16.382 --> 45:19.760
<i>Um, Roger Bowen,
uh, this is my son, Max.</i>

45:19.968 --> 45:21.595
<i>This is his bat.
He left it at school.</i>

45:21.804 --> 45:23.681
<i>Uh, listen, people
are upset and, uh,</i>

45:23.889 --> 45:25.724
<i>we should really...
Calm down, everybody!</i>

45:25.933 --> 45:27.851
<i>This is no way
to handle this situation.</i>

48:04.508 --> 48:05.634
<i>Thank you all for coming.</i>

48:06.134 --> 48:08.011
I think everybody here
is concerned

48:08.220 --> 48:09.429
about the safety of our streets.

48:09.638 --> 48:12.182
We have got to stick together.

48:12.391 --> 48:14.852
There is a killer in our town.

48:17.271 --> 48:19.189
I look at all these faces
and I...

48:19.398 --> 48:22.150
I don't want to lose
a single one of you.

48:22.359 --> 48:24.027
<i>Beverly made some bars,
and some coffee.</i>

48:24.236 --> 48:25.863
<i>It's on the table.
Help yourself, folks.</i>

48:27.197 --> 48:29.408
And... take care of each other.

48:35.372 --> 48:36.540
<i>Help yourself.</i>

48:37.499 --> 48:38.500
How's Bill?

48:38.709 --> 48:40.419
Oh, I'm worried about him.

48:40.627 --> 48:42.462
He's not feeling well.

48:42.671 --> 48:44.840
And he's so, oh,
down in the dumps.

48:45.048 --> 48:46.300
Uh, he can get that way.

48:46.508 --> 48:48.302
It's a winter thing.

48:48.510 --> 48:50.762
But he hasn't been
out of the house in over a week.

48:50.971 --> 48:52.180
He hasn't been out at all?

48:52.389 --> 48:54.474
Oh, hi, John. No.

48:54.683 --> 48:56.602
It's almost like he's afraid.

48:56.810 --> 48:58.145
<i>I think he's worried
about slipping on the ice</i>

48:58.353 --> 49:00.063
<i>or something.</i>

49:00.272 --> 49:03.734
<i>John? Why don't you
go see him? He'd like that.</i>

49:05.152 --> 49:06.153
<i>Hi, John.</i>

49:06.528 --> 49:07.571
<i>Hey, Brooke.</i>

49:08.614 --> 49:11.199
You want some juice
or hot chocolate?

49:11.408 --> 49:12.951
His stomach is bothering him.

49:13.160 --> 49:15.245
Do you think I could get him
to go to the doctor?

49:15.454 --> 49:17.539
Or you could try this one.

49:17.748 --> 49:19.416
Mixture of rat poison
and metal filings.

49:20.667 --> 49:22.586
Oh, thank you.

49:43.565 --> 49:45.442
<i>Good to see you there.</i>

49:56.453 --> 49:59.665
"On what wings dare he aspire?"

50:00.666 --> 50:02.167
What?

50:02.376 --> 50:04.711
"What the hand...

50:04.920 --> 50:06.755
...dare seize the fire?"

50:10.384 --> 50:12.344
Just a poem.

50:14.805 --> 50:17.182
"Tyger, tyger burning bright

50:17.391 --> 50:19.685
"In the forests of the night

50:22.104 --> 50:24.314
"What immortal hand or eye

50:24.523 --> 50:27.609
could frame thy
fearful symmetry?"

50:35.033 --> 50:36.576
The poet...

50:37.536 --> 50:40.455
...is asking the tiger

50:40.664 --> 50:43.667
who made him and how.

50:50.215 --> 50:51.842
William Blake.

50:53.635 --> 50:55.595
He wrote two poems like that.

50:57.597 --> 51:00.308
"The Lamb" and "The Tyger."

51:02.602 --> 51:05.272
One who was made
of sweetness and love

51:06.481 --> 51:10.610
and one was forged
from terror and death.

51:12.279 --> 51:15.991
"When the stars
threw down their spears

51:16.199 --> 51:18.702
"and watered heaven
with their tears.

51:20.370 --> 51:23.457
"Did he smile his work to see?

51:25.667 --> 51:28.170
Did he who made
the Lamb make thee?"

52:43.537 --> 52:45.497
Hi, Mr. Crowley.

52:48.500 --> 52:50.627
Hi, how are you?

52:51.586 --> 52:52.838
How are you?

52:54.381 --> 52:55.757
How's your leg?

52:55.966 --> 52:57.843
Can I kill you?

53:01.596 --> 53:03.223
<i>And how is school?</i>

53:03.723 --> 53:06.101
It's fine.

53:06.309 --> 53:09.813
Everybody's afraid
but... that's pretty normal.

53:10.021 --> 53:12.232
- And are you afraid?
- No.

53:14.901 --> 53:17.320
Fear is a really weird thing.

53:17.529 --> 53:19.239
You know, people are,
people are afraid of things

53:19.447 --> 53:22.200
but they're never afraid
of their own actions.

53:25.871 --> 53:27.831
Well, it's -- it's like
that woman right there.

53:28.039 --> 53:28.707
<i>You know, she,</i>

53:28.915 --> 53:31.459
<i>she could be afraid
of getting hit by a car.</i>

53:31.668 --> 53:33.587
But she isn't afraid of crossing
the street, you know?

53:33.795 --> 53:35.964
<i>She's done it before.
It should be pretty easy.</i>

53:36.173 --> 53:39.009
She just waits until
she can't see any cars

53:39.217 --> 53:42.345
and cross out
carefully onto the ice.

53:42.554 --> 53:44.764
She's gonna do everything
she can to keep herself safe.

53:46.766 --> 53:48.602
<i>And there, there she goes.</i>

54:00.488 --> 54:01.907
She's fine.
She made it.

54:32.020 --> 54:34.147
He refuses
to go to the doctor.

54:34.356 --> 54:36.358
Oh, stop it woman.

54:36.566 --> 54:38.026
I'll be alright.

54:44.491 --> 54:46.701
Alright.

54:46.910 --> 54:48.995
Lower the seat and the cover.

54:54.876 --> 54:56.002
Oh.

54:57.254 --> 54:58.505
Oh.

54:59.923 --> 55:00.966
<i>Well, that's better.</i>

55:03.260 --> 55:06.721
You've been a big help
to me and Kay this winter, John.

55:09.349 --> 55:12.394
Seems like a dying thing.

55:12.602 --> 55:15.397
<i>Neighbors helping neighbors.</i>

55:17.399 --> 55:20.026
Alright, I've got you.
I've got you.

